'''Ange-Yoan Bonny''' (born 25 October 2003) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[forward (association football)|forward]] for {{Italian football updater|Internazionale}} club [[Inter Milan]]. Born in France, he represents the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast national team]].

==Club career==

===Chateauroux===
Bonny made his professional debut with [[LB Châteauroux|Châteauroux]] in a 2–1 [[Ligue 2]] loss to [[AS Nancy|Nancy]] on 31 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2020/10/31/france/ligue-2/association-sportive-nancy-lorraine/la-berrichonne-chateauroux/3287899/|title=Nancy vs. Châteauroux - 31 October 2020 - Soccerway|website=Soccerway}}</ref>

===Parma===
On 31 August 2021, Bonny joined [[Serie B]] side [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parmacalcio1913.com/2021/08/31/ange-yoan-bonny-e-un-giocatore-del-parma/|publisher=[[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]|title=ANGE-YOAN BONNY È UN GIOCATORE DEL PARMA|date=31 August 2021|language=it}}</ref> In his debut season in [[2024–25 Serie A|Serie A]], he emerged as his club's leading scorer, netting a total of six goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/article/premier-league-clubs-showing-interest-124400661.html |title=Premier League clubs showing interest in Parma's Ange-Yoan Bonny |publisher=Yahoo Sports |date=16 March 2025 }}</ref>

===Inter Milan===
On 5 July 2025, Bonny moved to [[Serie A]] club [[Inter Milan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/ange-yoan-bonny-joins-inter|publisher=[[Inter Milan]]|title=Ange-Yoan Bonny joins Inter|date=5 July 2025|access-date=5 July 2025}}</ref> Consequently, he reunited with his former Parma coach, [[Cristian Chivu]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/de/news/inter-milan-new-boy-declares-happy-to-reunited-with-chivu-i-want-to-learn-from-lautaro-thuram-41334504 |title=Inter Milan New Boy Declares: 'Happy To Reunited With Chivu, I Want To Learn From Lautaro & Thuram' |publisher=OneFootball |date=5 July 2025 }}</ref> A month later, on 25 August, he scored on his league debut for Inter in a 5–0 win against [[Torino FC|Torino]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report/_/gameId/736791 |title=Inter Milan smash Torino 5-0 to start Serie A in style |publisher=ESPN |date=26 August 2025 }}</ref>

On 4 October, Bonny scored and provided three assists in a 4–1 win over [[US Cremonese|Cremonese]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/story/_/id/46488015/ange-yoan-bonny-goal-assists-inter-milan-cremonese|title=Bonny gets goal, hat trick of assists to lead Inter Milan win|website=ESPN|date=4 October 2025|access-date=1 February 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/interview-bonny-mvp-inter-cremonese-2025-26|title=BONNY'S SHOW, WITH A GOAL AND THREE ASSISTS: "EVERYTHING FEELS WONDERFUL: HAPPY TO HAVE HELPED."|website=Inter Milan|date=5 October 2025|access-date=1 February 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
Bonny is a youth international for France, having played up to the [[France national under-21 football team|France U21]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parmacalcio1913.com/en/main-news/ange-yoan-bonny-the-assist-maestro-for-his-teammates/|title=ANGE-YOAN BONNY, THE ASSIST|website=Parma Calcio 1913}}</ref>

He was one of the players who were preliminary called-up with the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast national team]] by head coach [[Emerse Faé]], for the [[Exhibition match|friendly]] match against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] on 28 March 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afrik-foot.com/elye-wahi-dans-la-liste-des-elephants-cest-vrai-que-je-lui-avais-ferme-la-porte-emerse-fae-explique-sa-volte-face|title=Elye Wahi dans la liste des Eléphants : “c'est vrai que je lui avais fermé la porte”, Emerse Faé explique sa volte-face|website=afrik-foot.com|date=18 March 2026|language= French}}</ref>

On 8 May 2026, Bonny's request to switch allegiance to Ivory Coast was approved by [[FIFA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/48713201/fifa-oks-switch-france-ivory-coast-inter-milan-bonny|title=FIFA OKs switch from France to Ivory Coast for Inter Milan's Bonny|publisher=ESPN|date=8 May 2026}}</ref> A week later, on 15 May, he was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Peter |first=Mike |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c9360dwzl2lo |title=Zaha omitted from Ivory Coast World Cup squad |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=May 15, 2026 |access-date=May 22, 2026 |archive-date=May 17, 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260517065701/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c9360dwzl2lo |url-status=live}}</ref> Bonny made his debut on 4 June 2026, coming on as a 68th‑minute substitute in a 2–1 friendly win over France ahead of the World Cup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cwy2zry55j0t#Line-ups|title=France vs Ivory Coast: Friendlies stats and head-to-head|publisher=BBC|date=4 June 2026}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Born in France, Bonny is of [[Ivory Coast|Ivorian]] descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://africafoot.com/3-africains-dans-le-top-10-des-avant-centres-u21-les-mieux-valorises-du-cies/|title=3 Africains dans le top 10 des avant-centres U21 les mieux valorisés du CIES|first=Cafil|last=Pastoré|date=4 June 2024}}</ref>

